Shared_buffer:-
Suppose a user runs a query. PostgreSQL first checks whether the required data page is available in shared_buffers (memory).
If it is available (cache hit), PostgreSQL returns the result directly from memory.
If it is not available (cache miss), PostgreSQL reads the required data page from the disk, stores it in shared_buffers, and then returns the result to the user.
If the same query or another query requires the same data page again, PostgreSQL serves it directly from memory instead of reading it from the disk again.
By default, PostgreSQL reads and stores data in pages of 8 KB.
Flow of query :--
                Query
                  │
                  ▼
         Check shared_buffers
                  │
          ┌───────┴────────┐
          │                │
     Cache Hit        Cache Miss
          │                │
          ▼                ▼
 Return Data         Read from Disk
 from Memory               │
                           ▼
              Store Data in shared_buffers
                           │
                           ▼
                    Return Data to User

Interview_Version:-
When a user runs a query, PostgreSQL first checks shared_buffers.
If the required data page is already in memory, it returns the result from memory.
If the data page is not in memory, PostgreSQL reads it from the disk, stores it in shared_buffers, and then returns the result.
If the user runs the same query again, PostgreSQL can return the data directly from memory, which is much faster. PostgreSQL stores data in pages, and the default page size is 8 KB.

examples:-
how to set shared_buffer = total RAM * 25%
IF RAM IS 128GB Then = 128 *25% = 32GB ===> shared_buffer = 32GB  After changing this parameter required to restart the service.
how to check this parameter :- show shared_buffer; | cat /var/lib/pgsql/18/data/postgresql.conf | grep shared_buffer
